{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512883","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512883"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:02:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:02:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11970"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11970","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11970"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.1,0.14,0.49,0.21]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4562"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78445"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4562"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11970"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63807"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"1"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"197"},{"type":"tags","id":"254"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5207"},{"type":"tags","id":"5605"},{"type":"tags","id":"5617"},{"type":"tags","id":"5620"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6830"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6843"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26787"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78445"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old man is brought to the Emergency Department after sustaining a significant crush injury while working on a building construction site. A concrete slab fell from the second storey of the building onto his legs. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his GCS is 6 (E1V2M3). He has a cervical collar in situ. He has obvious crush deformities to both legs. Due to his current conscious level, a rapid sequence induction is required.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following agents should be AVOIDED?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atracurium","Rocuronium","Ketamine","Succinylcholine","Propofol"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESuccinylcholine \u003C/strong\u003Eis a depolarising neuromuscular blocking agent that SHOULD NOT be used in this patient. It should not be used in patients at high risk of hyperkalaemia, as it may cause hyperkalaemia itself. High risk patients include those with significant trauma, rhabdomyolysis or recent burns. Succinylcholine\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eis also contraindicated in patients with a personal history or family history of pseudocholinesterase deficiency, as its neuromuscular effects may be prolonged and incredibly dangerous (pseudocholinesterase deficiency resulting in prolonged succinylcholine action is also known as \u0027Sux Apnoea\u0027).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtracurium\u003C/strong\u003E is a type of non-depolarising neuromuscular blocker which falls into the benzylisoquinolonium subgroup. This agent is not broken down by pseudocholinesterase and doesn\u0027t influence potassium concentrations, so it could be used in this patient. Atracurium should however be used with caution in patients with asthma, as it results in histamine release. It has also been shown to have adverse cardiovascular events more commonly than other benzylisoquinolonium non-depolarising neuromuscular blockers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERocuronium \u003C/strong\u003Eis a type of non-depolarising neuromuscular blocker which falls into the amide subgroup. At a rapid sequence intubation dose of 1.2mg/kg, onset time is similar to that of succinylcholine (approx. 60 seconds) and as such is frequently utilised in these trauma situations. The metabolism of this agent is not under the influence of pseudocholinesterase. It could safely be used in this patient. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropofol \u003C/strong\u003Eis a sedative agent often used as part of rapid sequence intubation and sedation maintenance and would be a suitable option for this patient. It is frequently used in rapid sequence inductions due to its rapid onset of action (15-45 seconds) however does require an infusion for maintaining sedation due to having a duration 5-10 minutes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKetamine\u003C/strong\u003E can be used as an induction agent for rapid sequence intubation and could be used in this patient. It is often used if the patient is haemodynamically unstable or if they have reactive airways disease. It should be used with caution in patients with known cardiovascular disease as it can cause hypertension and tachycardia. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In patients with burns, crush injuries, rhabdomyolysis or disorders with increased potassium concentration, administration of succinylcholine may lead to severe and potentially lethal hyperkalaemia.","Non-depolarising neuromuscular blockers like rocuronium and atracurium are safer alternatives to succinylcholine in patients at risk of hyperkalaemia."],"references":["Hovgaard HL, Juhl-Olsen P. Suxamethonium-Induced Hyperkalemia: A Short Review of Causes and Recommendations for Clinical Applications. Crit Care Res Pract. 2021 Feb 25;2021:6613118. doi: 10.1155/2021/6613118. PMID: 33708444; PMCID: PMC7932779. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7932779/","Caldwell JE, Lau M, Fisher DM. Atracurium versus vecuronium in asthmatic patients. A blinded, randomized comparison of adverse events. Anesthesiology. 1995 Nov;83(5):986-91. doi: 10.1097/00000542-199511000-00012. PMID: 7486185. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/7486185/","Strachan J, Frise M. Life-threatening hyperkalaemia after succinylcholine. Lancet. 2020 Jan 18;395(10219):e9. doi: 10.1016/S0140-6736(19)32493-6. PMID: 31954472. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31954472/","D\u00e9pret F, Peacock WF, Liu KD, Rafique Z, Rossignol P, Legrand M. Management of hyperkalemia in the acutely ill patient. Ann Intensive Care. 2019 Feb 28;9(1):32. doi: 10.1186/s13613-019-0509-8. PMID: 30820692; PMCID: PMC6395464. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30820692/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63807"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11970"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63807","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63807"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-10T19:02:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-10T19:03:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4562"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78445"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"26","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/26"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd7c